Do you have a black box in your car?
While U.S. road designers are trying to find money to repair a crumbling system of roadways, many are starting to see a solution in a small black box, neatly mounted on your car’s dashboard.
These devices, which track every mile that a motorist drives and transmits this information to officials, are at the center of a controversial attempt to modernize America’s outdated highway financing system, undertaken by Washington and the state’s planning authorities.
Usually, the boring arena of highway planning has unexpectedly given rise to intense debates and colorful alliances.
The libertarians have joined environmental groups in lobbying to give the government the right to use small boxes to track the number of miles you drive and even, perhaps, the one where you drive them, and then to use that information when creating tax accounts.
Teapot movement in shock.
The American Civil Liberties Union is also deeply concerned and raises a number of questions regarding private life.
And while Congress cannot yet agree, continue or not, several states are not going to wait.
They’re thinking about how the next decade can move on to a system where drivers pay for every mile of the road they travel.
Thousands of motorists have already taken to the test these black boxes, some of which have the function of satellite tracking.
This is really necessary for our country.
“This is not the question on which we may have the right to choose,” said Hassan Ihrata, executive director of the Southern California Government Association, which is preparing plans to begin tracking the state of mile traveled by every Californian motorist by 2025.
There will be changes in how we pay these taxes.
There are already technologies for that.
The need for this is compounded by the lack of funds from the Government Road Construction Fund, which is funded by taxes that Americans pay on auto-fuels.
Americans don’t buy as much gas as they used to.
Cars travel more than a mile per gallon.
The federal tax, 18.4 cents per gallon, has not increased in 20 years.
Politicians do not want to raise the tax even by one cent at high gasoline prices.
“The gas tax is simply impossible to keep,” said Li Mannic, an expert on transport policy at the University of Minnesota.
In his state, 500 tracking devices have recently been installed on cars to test the faulty payment system.
“This will be the best alternative in the long run,” he said.
This is called a faulty user fee.
It is not surprising that this idea attracts city liberals, since with the help of taxes it will be possible to change the nature of trips to reduce the loading of roads and greenhouse gas emissions, for example.
Planned bodies in California are looking at this system in the process of developing strategies to achieve the targets set by the state's ambitious laws to combat global warming.
However, a member of the House of Representatives, Bill Schuster (Republican, Pennsylvania), chairman of the House Transport Committee, said he also sees the system as the most viable long-term alternative.
Proponents of the free market at the Reason Foundation are also delighted that they will force drivers to pay for every mile.
“It’s not just a tax that’s going to go into a black hole,” said Adrian Moore, vice president of political affairs Reason.
People pay directly for what they get.
The movement is also backed by two former U.S. transport ministers, who in 2011 called on Congress to move towards the wrong payment.
Last year, the U.S. Senate approved a $90 million pilot project involving about 10,000 cars.
However, the leaders of the House of Representatives rejected this proposal because of the fears of rural legislators representing voters who often have to travel many miles in their daily lives to get to work or to the city.
Several states and cities, however, follow this path on their own.
The biggest enthusiasm is manifested in the state of Oregon, where 5,000 drivers are drawn to participate in the largest experiment in the country.
These drivers will soon pay the state for mileage instead of a gasoline tax.
In Nevada, the pilot project has already been completed.
In New York, it is being considered.
Illinois will test it on a limited basis with the participation of trucks.
And the I-95 coalition, which includes the transport departments of 17 states of the East Coast (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia and Florida), is exploring how they will be able to make these changes.
This concept has not been universally recognized.
In Nevada, where about 50 volunteer cars were recently equipped with these devices, drivers were concerned that the government could track every step of their lives.
“The concern about the ‘big brother’ and such things is a big problem,” said Alouddin Khan, who heads the Nevada Department of Transportation’s strategy and efficiency management department.
It wasn’t what people wanted.
When the tests were in full swing, the U.S. Civil Liberties Union in Nevada warned on its website: “It will not be difficult to turn these devices into full-scale surveillance devices.”
There is no need to create a huge, massive technological infrastructure that will inevitably expand to store records of the daily movements of individual citizens.
Nevada is one of several states where there are difficult searches for low-cost technology that would allow the state authorities to take into account the miles driven by the car, but without information about the place and time.
If you can do that, Khan said, society will feel more at ease.
The search for this technology led some state agencies to a small young company in California called True Mileage.
Initially, the company did not assist in the collection of state taxes.
It sought to enter the developing auto insurance market, where drivers pay on the basis of the race.
But the devices it tests attract road designers because they don’t use GPS and provide a limited amount of information that is periodically downloaded using a modem.
“People will be more likely to do this if you don’t track their speed and don’t track their location,” Ryan Morrison, CEO of True Mileage, said in a statement.
There have been several major errors in some of these state pilot programs.
There are far less expensive and less burdensome ways to do so.
In Oregon, designers are experimenting with providing drivers with a variety of options.
They can choose a device with or without GPS.
Or they can completely abandon the device, deciding instead to pay a fixed fee based on the average number of miles that all residents of the state travel.
In other places, they hope to sell the idea to the guarded public, forcing the devices to do more, not less.
In New York City, transport officials are seeking to develop a tax-deductible device that will also accept parking bill payments, provide “payments as you drive” insurance, and collect a real-time speed data pool from other drivers to fly away.
“Automobilists will be drawn to the participation of the benefits that they will offer,” – says in the document of urban design.
Some designers of transportation systems, however, wonder if all the talk about faulty payment is just a huge distraction.
In the city’s San Francisco Bay Transportation Commission, officials say that Congress could very simply overcome the bankruptcy of the Trusted Highway Construction Fund by raising taxes on gasoline.
An additional one-time or annual tax could be levied from drivers of hybrid cars and other persons whose vehicles do not use a lot of gasoline to pay their fair share.
“There’s no need for radical surgery when all you need to do is take aspirin,” said Randy Rentschler, director of the Commission on Legislation and Public Relations.
If we do that, hundreds of millions of drivers will worry about their private lives and a lot of other things.
