Goldman Sachs warns of risks to the Russian economy
Goldman Sachs has warned about the growing risks for Russia’s main driver of fragile economic growth – consumption.
This is primarily a crisis of defaults on unsecured consumer loans and massive reductions in workers.
Our main concern now is not that growth has slowed down, but rather the structure of this growth.
Recently, it is entirely due to consumption, which almost does not reduce turnover,” said Goldman Sachs’ chief economist for Russia, Klemens Grafe, presenting yesterday a quarterly report of the investment bank on the Russian economy.
Currently, the nominal wage growth in Russia is about 10%.
At 6% inflation, it will be able to provide future consumer demand around the current level, Goldman Sachs expects.
But the profitability of Russian companies is falling, so, most likely, they will deal with the optimization of personnel costs.
Today we see a significant increase in the share of wages in GDP: if wages increase by 10%, then GDP - by only 2%, - explained Mr. Grafe.
The companies faced a reduction in profitability.
If it does not grow, it can lead to layoffs and unemployment growth.
The Russian business cannot raise wages, comments the chief economist Barclays Capital on Russia and the CIS Vladimir Pantyushin.
Unemployment is close to historical minimums, competition for workers is high.
In order to shift employees from the side or keep the current ones, employers have to raise wages.
The consumption in Russia of support is alive and very fast growth in consumer credit.
According to Mr. Grafe, due to extremely high consumer borrowing rates, this type of lending does not have a multiplier effect on the economy of the country.
“We have not seen any benefits for the economy from the growth of consumer credit, the money does not divide the economy, but returns to the same banks in the form of interest payments,” the economist said.
But the problem is, Goldman Sachs is expecting a delay in unsecured loans.
They are taken mainly by the poor people, who have nothing to provide.
The percentages for such loans are high.
As a result, they are not returned more often,” said Mr. Grafe.
Therefore, the second threat to the growth of the economy in Russia is a possible crisis of default on unsecured loans.
The Director of the Bank Institute of WSE Vasily Solodkov already sees signs of a looming banking crisis.
Small credit organizations, without having access to the cheap resources that the state banks have, were forced to attract the population's funds below high interest rates.
In response, the state banks went on the path of war and began to reduce credit rates, - continues the economist.
Small credit institutions cannot issue loans at the same percentage, otherwise they will have a negative interest margin.
If the state banks do not give up dumping, Russia is in danger of a full-fledged banking crisis, believes Vasily Solodkov.
Deprivation of licenses from a number of banks in recent weeks has seen economists as a precursor to the mass collapse.
“The state banks themselves will not cope with this situation: the deposit insurance system was initially not designed for a systemic crisis,” the head of the institute warns.
But consumption growth will slow even without a crisis of non-payments, according to the investment bank, - due to the refusal to index salaries of civil servants and military, laid out in the current version of the draft budget.
Partial impact on consumption will be mitigated by the freezing of tariffs of natural monopolies (and, as a result, a decrease in inflation).
But only partially: if investments do not grow (and there are no prerequisites for this yet – see the report), consumption growth will still slow down, Goldman Sachs is confident.
Vladimir Pantyushin of Barclays Capital has not yet seen the prerequisites for the implementation of pessimistic scenarios.
“The main risk is the continued drop in oil prices,” he says.
According to him, Russia’s economy will begin to decline at oil prices below $90/barre.
Goldman Sachs also noted that the Central Bank is not yet in a position to reduce interest rates in the economy.
There is a paradoxical picture: inflation has decreased, and banks have started raising rates.
This may mean that they did not trust the Central Bank, which announced the transition to targeting inflation,” said Clement Grafe.
The Central Bank’s interest rate policy does not affect market rates, it only affects interbank lending rates.
"For the Central Bank, this is a breach of all hope," Clemens Grafe said.
The money received at the Central Bank auctions, banks use not to credit the economy, but to manage their liquidity
Once the rate is reduced, the exchange rate immediately changes, which means that the funds are trying to go on speculation against the ruble.
“Early or later, the Central Bank will realize that this strategy is not working,” Mr. Grafe said, noting that the government is planning to release the ruble in “free swimming” by the end of 2015.
But it will either have to do it sooner, or raise the central bank’s key rate (5.5%), he believes.
According to him, the ruble rate is now artificially increased by 10%.
I only rub one way - to weaken, - concludes the expert.
But if the central bank plunges in the financiers, despite the shadow of doubt, that the liquidation of the currency corridor is not part of the policy to weaken the ruble, it can break the ruble much stronger.
