Frontier Airlines will charge for hand luggage.
Frontier Airlines plans to charge passengers up to $100 for carrying a manual bet on board their flight.
Frontier Airlines plans to start charging up to $100 for a manual bet and $2 for coffee or gas, although their announcement on Wednesday said passengers would be able to leave the entire bank.
The new fee for the manual deposit is applied to bags in the upper luggage compartments, so small bags placed under the seat will remain free of charge.
Frontier said it would charge $25 if the fee is paid in advance, and $100 if travelers would pay only after leaving for the landing.
Frontier spokeswoman Kate O’Malley said a $100 fee should make passengers take care of the payment in advance.
“We don’t want to charge for it,” she said.
The airlines began charging for the first and second bags, which were delivered in baggage, in 2008.
Passengers trying to avoid these charges charge as much as they can in a handbag placed in the upper luggage compartments, which is why these compartments often lack space.
Fees are one of the ways to get passengers to spend less on board.
O’Malley said that this new fee is actually not for the sake of making money.
The fact is that the most loyal Frontier customers claim that finding a place in the top luggage compartments is becoming more and more difficult.
Passengers who purchase tickets on the airline’s website will not have to pay.
This means that one passenger in a row at the departure of the Frontier flight may be able to carry the bag for free, while the next passenger in a row may pay $100 for the same bag.
O’Malley said the change in procedures on the website and at Frontier registration booths is meant to ensure that passengers will know about the collection before they get off the ground.
The new Frontier collection for the manual bet will not start to charge until summer, although the date has not yet been set.
Passengers often complain about baggage charges and other charges, but airlines love them.
They claim that baggage handling costs money, and passengers who need this service have to pay for it.
Many on Wall Street consider the addition of baggage charges as a sign that airlines are charging enough money to cover the cost of airline tickets after several years of losses.
However, most of them did not touch the fees for the manual bet.
Spirit Airlines Inc. introduced the first manual layoff three years ago, and another Allegiant Air discounter later followed suit.
The only other airline with such a charge is Hungarian Wizz Air, said airline consultant Jay Sorensen, who closely monitors additional charges.
According to his estimate in a December 2011 report, the hand-betting fee brings Spirit $50 million a year.
Sorensen, a former top manager of Midwest Airlines, recently flew a Spirit flight, and he was interested in finding it at the departure when passengers face an unusual Spirit charge for a hand bet.
“The landing process was the smoothest of those I’ve seen in my career at airlines,” he said.
I was expecting to see a cross of teeth and the appearance of a fight at the exit to the landing.
The plane was full, he said, “and the landing passed quickly.”
Frontier also follows Spirit for a fee of $2 for coffee, tea, gas or juice.
Frontier said that passengers who receive a gas or juice can leave their entire bank and that a cup of coffee will be provided free of charge.
It will still be free to distribute the water.
US Airways briefly tried to charge for drinks in 2008, but refused to do so seven months later, after passengers began complaining and no other major airline followed suit.
Frontier’s initiative to charge for hand luggage, when passengers do not buy tickets directly from the airline, is its last step in attracting customers to its website.
Airlines pay online ticket sellers, such as Orbitz, from $10 to $25 for each ticket sold.
This gave all airlines an incentive to encourage passengers to buy tickets directly from them, rather than to contact a travel agency online.
However, Frontier has gone further in this area.
In September, she began giving twice as many bonus miles as a frequent flyer to customers who bought tickets through an online travel agency.
On Wednesday, she cut the premium number of miles to 25 percent of the mile trip.
Thus, a trip 1000 miles from Frontier, purchased from an online travel agency, would allow you to get 250 miles.
In addition, passengers can choose a seat in advance only if they buy tickets directly on the Frontier website.
Frontier has a loyal customer base in her hometown of Denver, but her business is shrinking and becoming a loser.
Revenue fell by 9 percent, and flight opportunities fell by almost 13 percent in the first quarter, according to financial results released Wednesday by parent company Republic Airways Holdings Inc.
The Republic is trying to repair Frontier’s finances as part of the airline’s sale.
