The Japanese electronics manufacturer, Sony Corporation, has completed the last quarter with a net loss of 19.3 billion yen, or $197 million, cut the forecast for earnings for the current financial year.
Sony’s results for the period from July to September 2013 turned out to be more daunting than expected, which is due to the fall in demand for TVs, video cameras and personal computers produced by the Japanese corporation.
Sony’s television business, which brought the company’s first operating profit of 5.2 billion yen in the second quarter in three years, fell again to 9.3 billion yen of operating loss in the reporting period.
The Japanese consumer electronics market is going through tough times, especially as demand for televisions has fallen.
And while competitors are striving to find a way out of a difficult situation, Sony continues to focus on the consumer segment.
For example, one of Sony’s main rivals, Panasonic, has recently shifted its focus to industrial components: here, sales of the company are growing at a high rate, especially due to automotive systems and environmentally friendly technologies.
As a result, by the end of the fiscal year, which will end in March 2014, Sony expects to receive 179 billion yen of operating profit against the previously expected 230 billion yen.
At the same time, according to Thomson Reuters, analysts assumed that this figure would be significantly higher and would amount to 221 billion yen.
In an effort to get out of the crisis, Sony is expanding the product line.
In the middle of this month, it was announced the start of sales of “smart” watches from a Japanese corporation, given a number of fashionable features, which will allow you to get rid of the need for 100 times a day to get out of your smartphone pocket.
After Sony lowered its annual profit and revenue forecast, the company’s shares at the opening in Tokyo lost more than 11% in the morning, dropping to the level of 1668 yen for a single share.
The gene of speech has been a stimulant of synapse formation
Scientists at Johns Hopkins University and Mount Sinai Medical School have discovered a protein that allows the “talking gene” Foxp2 to perform its function, stimulating the formation of new connections between neurons.
The study is published in Science, on the magazine’s website you can read its brief content.
The Foxp2 gene is the first known gene whose function is directly related to speech.
His role was established in 2001 thanks to the discovery of a family of several people who could not pronounce words correctly and sometimes did not even understand each other themselves.
The researchers found that family members had a violation of the work of the Foxp2 gene, but how it performs its function remains unknown.
In a new study, biologists have shown that at least some of its functions Foxp2 performs as a stimulus for the formation of new brain synapses associated with speech formation.
This is done by another gene, SRPX2.
The latter was discovered as a result of the search for factors that stimulate the formation of synapses.
SRPX2 was one of the 10 similar genes found by the authors, with only Foxp2 relying on its activity.
The fact that SRPX2 really affects vocalization, scientists confirmed in an experiment on mice.
When the activity of the gene in animals was artificially reduced, they shouted less when separated from the mother.
If the activity of the gene was restored, the frequency of the emitted sounds was restored.
Previously, mice were also shown to be related to the vocalization of Foxp2 itself.
The animals that introduced a human copy of the gene were eating more actively and at a lower frequency than normal mice.
So far, however, scientists don’t know whether Foxp2’s work is related and, accordingly, managed by SRPX2 to purely “mechanical” properties of sound formation or more subtle processes.
