And yet there is an interesting moment lost in the retelling of an ancient fairy tale.
Why should an independent Scotland comply with Europe’s orders at all?
Why change the London yoke to the Brussels yoke, especially now?
Here is the real European news: the great post-war plan to unite Europe has finally stalled.
With the euro crisis, the project “Europe” is officially dead.
Throughout the European Union, parties that oppose the EU or for the abolition of the euro as a single currency are gaining strength.
Even in Germany, the party of Eurosceptics “Alternative for Germany” – founded only this year – emerged from nowhere and received almost five million votes in the September federal elections, thus essentially pushing out the “Free Democrats” (an analogy of our “Liberal Democrats”).
There has always been an internal opposition to the plan to create a federal Europe.
However, the current economic crisis has become a turning point.
The austerity measures introduced by Berlin and the European Central Bank, and the loopholes imposed on national economies through the preservation of a single currency, have led many people to believe that the “Europe” project has gone too far.
The euro crisis has little to do with the fact that national governments are working under excessive budget deficits – it was only fair for Greece.
In fact, the Eurosystem has blocked its members at exchange rates beneficial to German exporters, which German politicians want to keep.
Without the possibility of devaluing the national currency, southern Europe is in a precarious position on production opportunities compared to Germany.
The only way to save is to cut salaries and government spending, which is actively supported by Berlin.
The current problems of the budget and currency are a deeper problem of Europe’s productive capacities.
As a result of the set of “green” energy measures implemented by Brussels – a cipher that means subsidizing French and German energy companies at the expense of the consumer – the European industry pays twice as much for electricity and four times as much for gas as the US.
These are paralyzingly unfavorable price conditions, as we have already seen in the Granjmut.
No wage freezes in the world will stop the crushing victory of cheap U.S. shale gas over the European petrochemical industry.
The result is a revolt, especially in France, once the fiercest supporter of the EU.
After the war, the French political elite saw the EU as a way to control Germany and put Paris on the same level as Washington.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a means of gaining political legitimacy, and has already imposed its own economic policy on Europe, leaving France’s ruined economy in a dire state.
The result – the right-wing anti-EU Marine Le Pen party “National Front” has just won decisive additional elections, dropping the ruling Socialist Party to third place.
The Front is now the most popular party in France with 24 percent of the vote — a timely warning to British Labour that it cannot be based on the assumption that a split between the right will automatically turn out in favor of the left.
What does Le Pen do with its newly discovered popularity among the French white working class?
It wants to use the EU elections next year to create a bloc in the European Parliament against the EU and against the single currency.
If – and this is very likely – the parties against the EU get support in these elections, such a bloc will be able to take the dominant position in the European Parliament for the first time.
This is my view: soon growing sentiments against the EU and against the single currency in Europe are united to destroy the euro.
The EU will not disappear, but it will once again become something of a flamboyant “Europe (sovereign) nations” that General de Gaulle liked.
Germany and several of its dependent economies may save the euro, but France and southern Europe will restore their own currencies.
I suppose the UK is distancing itself from this project, hoping to get closer to the United States.
However, Washington’s growing interest in the Pacific indicates the likelihood that Britain will remain unattended in the cold of the Atlantic.
