Early sexual maturation: Aging earlier
African-American and Latino-American girls tend to reach sexual maturity earlier than their white counterparts, according to research.
Physical changes do not mean that sexual maturation is close
There is no evidence that hormones or other chemicals are to blame.
Experts believe that the obesity epidemic may be one of the triggers for early sexual maturation.
The tendency to early sexual maturity is not so pronounced in boys
Former CNN correspondent Pat Etheridge is a journalist specializing in child health and family issues.
Should mothers be afraid if their daughter begins to form the beginnings of the mammary gland and grow forehead hair at 7 or 8 years old?
At the annual conference of the American Academy of Pediatrics this week in Orlando, Florida, pediatric endocrinologist Dr. Paul Kaplovitz explained that these early physical changes are fairly common among American girls and are a new norm.
“I spend a lot of time calming my parents – it usually doesn’t mean a rapid onset of full sexual maturity,” Kaplovitz said.
Obvious signs of development, such as growing breasts, forehead and underarm hair and body odor, appear earlier in girls.
But there has been only a slight shift in the age of the menarche (the first menstruation) over the last four decades.
In the United States, the average age is 12.5 years and decreased from 12.75 in 1970.
“After the breast begins to develop, it takes at least two to three years before the menarche,” said Kaplovitz, who is also the author of the book “Early sexual maturation in girls: how to deal with this common problem.”
Time is the most accurate test of how sexual maturation will progress.
There is a discussion about what constitutes the actual onset of sexual maturity, but is considered “premature” when breast augmentation is accompanied by a sharp increase in growth up to 8 years.
In most cases, the process will slow down or slow down – this is what the pediatrician can closely monitor.
Faster progression may serve as a basis for analysis by an endocrinologist to rule out serious problems such as tumors or cysts.
There are procedures to delay early menstruation and prevent another consequence: premature aging of the bones, which can eventually lead to slowed growth and low growth in adulthood.
Recommendations for drug or hormonal therapy are based on the child's age, level of development, growth rate and emotional maturity.
Psychosocial aspects are also important.
Kaplovitz cautioned with drugs, but admitted that “repression of sexual maturity can alleviate behavioral problems and the feeling of girls that they are different from peers.”
Another big problem is clear: parents just don’t want their very young daughters to have menstruation.
“They are concerned about the risk of pregnancy or even how they deal with hygiene issues,” Kaplovitz said.
“It was a shock,” recalls one woman, whose daughter began menstruation at the age of 10.
Although there were signs and we were talking about menstruation, she was not emotionally ready.
She came home from school scared and upset that she was the first of her friends.
There are many out-of-state theories about the causes of early sexual maturity.
However, there is no consistent evidence that hormones in milk or other foods are to blame, chemicals in the environment, or sexual messages in the media.
In boys – as in girls – sexual maturation occurs earlier.
Kaplovitz argues that the condition, which has the most weight, is an epidemic of obesity.
In 2001, he helped conduct a study of girls from 6 to 9 years old, which links the amount of fat in the body with the duration of sexual maturation.
Other data confirm this conclusion, but there are many other contributing factors.
In this country, African-American and Latino-American girls tend to reach sexual maturity earlier than their white counterparts.
There are different explanations.
All over the world, early sexual maturation is likely to affect everything from economic conditions and climate to genes.
Another mystery: although boys have hair on their face and forehead at a younger age, the tendency to fully early sexual maturation is not as pronounced as in girls.
Other doctors participating in the AAP conference confirmed the complexity of the topic.
The appearance of pimples and pubic hair is found even in infants and children of noble age.
“We need to be careful about how we determine the true onset of sexual maturity,” said Dr. Lawrence Silverman, a pediatric endocrinologist at Gorieb Children’s Hospital in Morristown, New Jersey.
Parents should not be ashamed to receive instructions from the pediatrician on how to talk to their child.
“This could mean a conversation earlier than expected,” Kaplovitz explained.
If you remain calm, your child will usually respond well.
Girls who bloom early need proof that even when this happens before the laying, this process is a normal part of life.
