A new anti-nicotinic vaccine may derail the pleasure smoking process
Scientists have developed an anti-nicotine vaccine that could eliminate the process of smoking pleasure cigarettes.
One dose of the vaccine has been able to protect mice from nicotine dependence for a lifetime.
Further tests are needed before the start of the human trials, which will take several years, but Professor Ronald Crystall of Wells Cornell Medical College in New York said the first results are encouraging.
“We very much hope that such a strategy to use the vaccine can finally help millions of smokers who have tried to quit by trying all the methods available on the market today, but have found that their nicotine dependence is strong enough to help them overcome it.”
The new vaccine contains a harmless virus that was designed to carry genetic information for the production of anti-nicotine antibodies.
The virus selectively infects the liver cells, which then begin to produce a stable stream of antibodies.
Antibodies track any nicotine molecules in the blood, neutralizing them before they reach the brain, preventing a smoker from getting a nicotine hit.
In the tests, the vaccinated mice, who were subsequently given nicotine, continued their normal activity.
And mice that didn’t get the vaccine “relaxed,” and this is a sign that nicotine came to their brains, the researchers say.
These experiments are described in the journal Science Translational Medicine.
The previous tobacco vaccines were unsuccessful because they contained antibodies to the vaccine.
In order to maintain high levels of antibodies, the stakes had to be made so often that they turned out to be expensive and impractical.
But the cost of the new vaccine is likely to be much lower because it turns liver cells into factories of antibodies.
Professor Crystall said that if a future human vaccine were completely safe, it could be given to children before they have a desire to try a cigarette, preventing nicotine addiction.
But it is more likely that it will be used by smokers to quit smoking.
“They will know that if they start smoking again, they won’t get pleasure from this because of the nicotine vaccine, and it can help them get rid of this habit,” he said.
British scientists said the results were interesting, but warned that further research was needed.
