Thus, there is still no “Words with Friends” — an intellectual internet game in which actor Alex Baldwin played on his smartphone in 2011 when a suspected case occurred: the actor was removed from the plane by American Airlines for refusing to turn off the device at the time.
And heavier devices, such as laptops, will still need to be put in the luggage compartment, as they can hurt someone if they fly all over the salon.
Calls from a mobile phone in flight will also still be banned.
Regulatory powers over telephone calls belong to the Federal Communications Commission, not the FAU.
FAU may remove the ban on some electronic devices during take-off and landing
Last month, Mark Rosenker of the National Transportation Safety Council, a national transportation safety expert at CBS News, said cell phones are still considered a risk.
“Cell phones are really a problem, not only because they potentially can create interference for navigation devices, but we know thanks to the FKS that they can create interference for cell communications when the aircraft is in the air,” Rosenker said.
The industry advisory committee, set up by the FAU to study the issue, recommended last month that the government allow a wider use of personal electronic devices.
In recent years, the pressure on the FAU has increased in order to reduce restrictions on their use.
Critics, such as Missouri Democratic Senator Claire McCaskill, argue that there are no strong security-related grounds for the ban.
Compliance with restrictions is also becoming increasingly difficult to ensure, as the use of devices has become ubiquitous.
Some studies show that up to a third of passengers forget or ignore instructions to turn off their devices.
The FAU began restricting the use of electronic devices by passengers in 1966 in response to reports of interference to navigation and communication equipment, when passengers began to carry FM radio receivers – high-tech gadgets of the time.
The new airliners are much more dependent on electrical systems than previous generations of aircraft, but they are also being developed and approved by the FAU as resistant to electronic interference.
The airlines have been offering passengers the use of Wi-Fi at cruising altitude for several years now.
Aircraft modified for Wi-Fi systems are also more resistant to interference.
The vast majority of liners are adapted for wider use of electronic devices according to new guidelines, Warta said.
Today’s electronic devices usually emit radio signals that are much lower in power than previous generations of devices.
Devices for reading e-books, for example, emit only minimal signals when scrolling through pages.
But the signals become more powerful when the devices download or send the data.
Among those who sought to mitigate restrictions on the use of electronic devices by passengers was Amazon.com.
In 2011, representatives of the company loaded an entire airliner with their devices to read Kindle e-books and flew on it to check for problems, but never found them.
Members of the FAU Advisory Committee expressed mixed feelings about whether the use of devices poses any risk.
Douglas Kidd of the National Association of Air Passengers said he believes the interference from the devices is real, even if the risk is minimal.
Other members of the committee said that there are only separate messages from pilots confirming that the devices can create disruptions to aviation systems, and most of those messages are very old.
However, the Committee recommended that the FAU allow pilots to require passengers to turn off the devices while boarding the devices under limited visibility conditions.
A group of representatives of the tourism industry welcomed these changes, calling them a healthy step towards passengers who are now using a host of technological devices.
“We are pleased that the FAU recognizes that passenger comfort is not incompatible with safety and protection,” said Roger Doe, Director General of the U.S. Tourist Association.
