Scientists have shed light on how the movements of the dog’s tail are related to her mood.
Earlier studies have shown that happy dogs roll their tail to the right side (from the dog’s point of view), while anxious dogs move their tail mainly to the left side.
But now scientists say that other representatives of the dog family may notice these subtle differences in tailings and react to them.
Professor Giorgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trent, says: “It is well known that people on the left and right sides of the brain are involved in different ways in the formation of constructors that cause positive or negative emotions.”
Here we tried to look at this and other species.
He added that just like in humans, dogs have the right side of the brain that controls the left side of the body and vice versa, and the two hemispheres play different roles in emotions.
To find out more about how dogs respond to the multiplexing of other dogs’ tails, the researchers looked at animals when they watched movies about other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of the animals and analyzed their behavior.
We’ll probably soon understand why their tails sometimes go one way, and sometimes they go the other way.
Professor Vallortigara said: “We showed dogs videos with dogs — either naturalistic versions or silhouettes to get rid of any other distorting factors, and we could manipulate tail movement and steer the tail more left or right.”
When the animals saw that the rest of the non-expressing dog was moving the tail to the right (from the point of view of the dog’s tail protruding), they remained completely relaxed.
But when they noticed that the tail leaned mainly to the left (again from the point of view of the dog’s tail protruding), their heart rate was happy and they looked anxious.
Professor Vallortigara said he didn’t think the dogs were intentionally communicating with each other through these movements.
In fact, he believes that dogs have learned from their experience, what movements they should worry about, and what they should not.
He notes: “If there are multiple encounters with other dogs and often their tail being thrown into one side is associated with more friendly behavior, and the right side gives less friendly behavior, the dog reacts based on this experience.”
The researchers say that these results can give owners, veterinarians and trainers a deeper understanding of their animal’s emotions.
A dog behavior expert, John Bradshaw, an invited scientist at the University of Bristol’s veterinary school, said it was not the first study to check whether dogs are of significance to the left and right sides.
Last year, a group of scientists from the University of Lincoln found that dogs turn their heads to the left if they look at an aggressive dog, and to the right if they look at a happy dog.
And in another scientific paper from the University of Victoria in Canada, he reported: “Dogs were more likely to approach a robot dog when its tail was tilted to the left rather than to the right rather than become anxious – the opposite behavior towards an Italian study.”
He said the differences could be due to the fact that dogs in various studies did not fully perceive animals in movies or robot dogs as dogs.
It could be useful to study how dogs react to real dogs, he explained.
“While there is enough evidence on different mammals that two hemispheres of the brain are used for different purposes, many details still need to be clarified, and dogs are no exception,” he said.
However, given the ease with which their behavior can be registered, we will probably soon understand why their tails sometimes go to one side and sometimes to the other.
