At his inauguration before the Supreme Constitutional Court, Morsi also became the first freely elected Islamic president of the Arab world and the fifth head of state in Egypt after the overthrow of the monarchy about 60 years ago.
He took an oath before 18 judges in black robes in a court building on the banks of the Nile, built in the style of an ancient Egyptian temple.
“We are striving for a better future, a new Egypt and a second republic,” Morsi said during a ceremony aired live on state television.
“Today, the Egyptian people laid the foundations for a new life – absolute freedom, genuine democracy and stability,” said Morsi, a 60-year-old American-educated engineer from the Muslim Brotherhood, a fundamentalist group that had been banned for most of the 84 years of its existence.
The building was guarded by hundreds of soldiers and police when Morsi arrived with a small cortet shortly after 11 a.m. local time.
Only a few hundred supporters gathered at the courthouse to welcome the new president, and, unlike the presidential pump of Mubarak’s time, the movement was stopped only for a short time to miss his autocolony along the usually lively road connecting the city center to the south.
Although Morsi was ridiculed as a non-charismatic "reserve wheel" by the Brotherhood, his personal prestige has risen sharply since his victory and Friday performance, in which he tried to present himself as a candidate not only against the Islamists, but also against all those who want to bring the 2011 mutiny to the end of the decade.
“Today, Egypt is a civil, national, constitutional and modern state,” Morsi, dressed in a blue business suit with a red collar, told judges in a wood paneled room where he took the oath.
Later, Morsi went to Cairo University, where he had to deliver his inaugural speech.
He was given an official reception with an army orchestra, which performed the state anthem, during which he stood on the stand "silently".
Field Marshal Hussain Tantavi was present.
His arrival was met with the slogan "Army and the People - One Hand", which scandalized hundreds of people gathered in the main lecture hall of the university.
Founded in 1908 as a pillar of secular education, Cairo University in the 1970s became a pillar of Islamist student groups.
Morsi took a symbolic oath on Friday on Tahrir Square, where an uprising that ended Mubarak’s authoritarian rule last year was born, and promised to return the powers of the president whose office was deprived by a military council that took over everything.
But having agreed to take an official oath before the court, and not before the parliament, as it is accepted, he is doing the will of the military, and this is a sign that the struggle for power will continue.
Mursi’s speech on Tahrir Square was filled with theatrical populist gestures.
