A journey through mud, rivers and jungles to provide free medical care
Dr. George Bwelle provides free medical care in rural areas in Cameroon <0xE2><0x86><0x92>
Bwelle and his team spend almost every weekend taking in hundreds of patients
There are not so many doctors in this West African country – only one in 5,000 people.
Vote here or through your mobile device.
Dr. George Bwelle is one of CNN’s top 10 heroes of 2013.
You can vote for him or any of the other top 10 heroes to make him a CNN Hero of the Year.
This person will receive $250,000 to continue his outstanding work.
For 21 years, George Bwelle saw his father come back to life and fall back into an unconscious state, wandering around hospitals that were not properly equipped to help him.
Bwelle was injured in a car crash in 1981 near Yaunde, the capital of Cameroon.
At first, he had only a broken arm, but the infection spread to the brain and caused a hematoma that reminded him of himself for the rest of his life.
“There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon,” George Bwelle said.
If we had the money, we would have taken it out of Cameroon.
Instead, Bwelle accompanied his father for years in overcrowded clinics and hospitals, receiving any treatment they could receive.
“It’s not easy,” Bwelle said.
You can leave the house at 5 a.m., run to the hospital to be the first, but you are no longer the first.
There are a lot of patients.
Some may die because of what they have to wait for.
The situation hasn’t changed much since Bwelle’s father died in 2002.
According to the World Health Organization, there is only one doctor per 5,000 people in Cameroon.
For comparison, the ratio in the United States is one doctor per 413 people.
And even if Cameroonians could go to the doctor, many of them would not be in their pocket.
Two out of five people in this country live below the poverty line, and nearly three-quarters of health care spending in it is private.
“Their only problem is poverty,” Bwelle said.
And because of poverty, they can’t enjoy their lives.”
Seeing the suffering of his father and many of his compatriots, Bwelle was determined to do something about it.
Last year, Dr. George Bwelle and his team of volunteers conducted 700 free operations.
He became a doctor himself and worked as a vascular surgeon at Yaoundé Central Hospital.
He also founded the non-profit organization ASCOVIME, which organizes trips to rural areas on weekends to provide free medical care.
Since 2008, he and his group of volunteers have assisted nearly 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday, he and up to 30 other people are loaded into the vans, tied to the roofs of medical supplies, and travel across a crossed area to visit those in need of village help.
They don't always have good luck.
Many times they had to push cars through rivers and dirt.
But when they arrive, they are met as real heroes: it is a holiday with songs and dances and the best rooms that can only be offered by locals.
Free medical care in these villages is indeed a reason for the holiday, and Bwelle with his wide smile and limitless energy is more than happy to join the fun.
The next morning, the brigade begins to receive hundreds of patients.
“We take 500 people on each trip,” Bwelle said.
They come from the whole district within a radius of 60 kilometers of the village, and they come on foot.
Each of these clinics on the weekend provides a variety of medical services.
Many people receive treatment from malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites, and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others may get skeletons, donated glasses, or free birth certificates — documents needed for schooling that many poor families simply can’t afford.
In the evening, the brigade conducts simple operations under local anesthesia.
Operations are usually performed in a school building, a municipality or a home; after the procedure, patients get up and go to the post-operative zone to free up space for the next person.
Using a generator to light up the operational and sanitary treatment equipment, Bwelle and his volunteers work until early Sunday morning.
It’s a slow pace, but the brigade’s aim is usually to help support rural musicians.
“They’ve been beating drums all night so we can wake up and keep working,” Bwelle said.
On Sunday, members of the brigade go back to the city, tired, but proud of their work.
This group, consisting of Cameroonian doctors and foreign medical students, has conducted 700 free surgeries over the past year, and they know that their help can be of great importance to those they help.
One person explained that the free surgery he received to treat the hernia will allow him to work again.
“It will change the future for me and my family,” the man said.
In addition to these clinical admissions on weekends and working at the hospital, surgeon Bwelle also works nights at private medical clinics around Yaunde.
It is this second work, he said, that provides 60% of the funding for his non-profit organization; the remaining funds are covered by private donations.
“I don’t even know when he’s sleeping,” said Katie O’Malley, a second-grade medical student at Drexel University in Philadelphia, a volunteer at the Bwell group.
He is always either in the hospital or trying to make money for the organization so that these campaigns can continue.
For future doctors and nurses such as O’Malley, who come from the US and Europe to join Bwelle in the realization of his tasks, this is an opportunity of practice that they would never have gotten at home.
“We were given the opportunity to assist in operations where we helped remove blood stains or keep the tools for Dr. Bwelle,” O’Malley said.
As a secondary school student, you would never get such an opportunity in America.
Volunteer students usually pay for their trip to Cameroon on their own, often arriving with donated medications.
But upon arrival in Yaoundé, their food, transportation, and training pay for Bwelle.
“He’s a hero, no doubt,” O’Malley said.
He gives his life to this organization, and his desire to help the people of Cameroon is endless.
For Bwell, an almost constant workload is not a hard test.
Helping others to live a happy life, fulfilling this promise to their father is something that brings him great joy.
“I’m so happy when I do this job,” said Bwelle.
And I think about my father.
I hope he sees what I'm doing.
I do this to make people laugh to reduce their pain.
Go to the ASCOVIME website and see how you can help.
